social_posts.post_text: I will always remember Jan 02, 2023, as a day of validation for the Native Tribal Nations in Minnesota by our Lieutenant Governor, Honorable Peggy Flanagan. To her inauguration, she wore a dress specially made for her by me that says, "IamAnishinaabe." Her scarf is a design by Sarah "Giizh" Agaton Howes. I am honored that she selected Minnesota Native Designers as a symbol of her commitment & pride in her Anishinaabe heritage. I used my very own original floral beadwork designs printed on fabric in turquoise blue and golden smokehide brown. The blouse & skirt are paired with matching ribbons of brown, gold, turquoise & navy blue significant to the traditional woman's ribbon skirt dating back to the 1800's. Her skirt is edged in hand-tanned smokehide, significant to the subsistence lifestyle of the original people of the woodlands. Miigwech Peggy!

I really enjoyed Barbie. And it was cathartic to attend with my kiddo and bff. We all cried.

That being said, there’s a “throwaway” line about Indigenous people and smallpox that didn’t land and wasn’t necessary. The imagery of Barbie version of Mt. Rushmore really missed the mark, too. So while I really liked the movie, it’s a reminder that Indigenous people need to be included in all aspects of the entertainment industry. Oh, and Hollywood, pay your writers and actors.

Today, Representative Jamie Becker-Finn announced that she would not seek re-election in 2024. While I’m sad that she won’t be a member of the legislature after next year, I’m incredibly grateful for the work she has done for Minnesotans - especially those navigating the justice system. Due to the leadership of Rep. Becker-Finn, both public defense and civil legal services have received long overdue investments that will ensure a more equitable and accessible justice system for years to come. Her legacy is her compassion, brilliance in debate on the MN House floor, ability to chair the heck out of a committee, bringing the voices of Indigenous Minnesotans into the halls of power, and always standing up for what’s right.

Repost: @indiancountrytoday In Lily Gladstone's Golden Globe acceptance speech, Gladstone spoke some of her Blackfeet language and thanked those that helped her reach this moment.

“I'm so grateful that I can speak even a little bit of my language, which I'm not fluent enough up here. Because in this business, Native actors used to speak their lines in English and then the sound mixers would run them backwards to accomplish Native languages on camera,” Gladstone said. “This is an historic win, it doesn't belong to just me. I'm holding it with all of my beautiful sisters.”

"And this is for every little rez kid, every little urban kid, every little Native kid out there who has a dream, who is seeing themselves represented in our stories, told by ourselves, in our own words, with tremendous allies and tremendous trust," Gladstone added.

Gladstone became the first Native woman to win the Golden Globe award for best actress in a dramatic film, "Killers of the Flower Moon," Sunday night.
